			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Leadership AAs<a name="74455"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Mar 15 05 9:01 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>The example I'm about to give may not be typical at all, and dsavereide's and Nhacsii's advice looks to be sound advice for dealing with normal &quot;pickup&quot; groups, but definitely not the case in my experience.  Granted, however, my normal xp group is <b>tight</b> and we've been grouping for years.  We've got an esp thing going on most of the time and just &quot;feel&quot; what each other is doing.
<br />

<br />
We've got an SK as MT, and, yes, she's smart.  We've got a great chanter for primary CC, BL and Rogue on DPS, me (bard) on pulls/pre-CC/pre-slow/pre-debuff, and our Cleric for heals.  Early on, we had our cleric on 100% Leadership AA(it stacked up (earned) quickly).
<br />

<br />
We find that both Delegate MT and Mark NPC are both <b>HIGHLY</b> used tools for us.  Sometimes I bring in 2 or 3 mobs on purpose and as I'm running backward into camp, I watch for the MT's &quot;brackets&quot; on whatever she picks (for her target) and I mezz-park the other two (for the chanter to take over mezz on).  After the chanter takes over (mezz), she marks the mobs in successive order (&quot;1&quot;, &quot;2&quot;, &quot;3&quot;, etc.).  Most of the time she is correct, but it is ALWAYS our SK (MT) that is the final decision maker.  Probably 99% of the time, our MT follows the suggested order, but when she doesn't, she usually has good reasons.
<br />

<br />
This may not be how some folks would do it, but it works <b>TIGHT</b> for us.  We feel like we can take on nearly the same content that two normal pickup groups could together.
<br />

<br />
</span></td>
